  "steps": [
    {
      "id": "intro",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Colors and word order",
      "body": "# Colors and clothing\n\nThe most important colors in Spanish:\n\n- **rojo** — red\n- **azul** — blue\n- **verde** — green\n- **blanco** — white\n- **negro** — black\n- **amarillo** — yellow\n\nThe key difference from English: the color goes **after** the noun, not before.\n\n- *la camisa **roja*** — the red shirt (literally: the shirt red)\n- *el vestido **azul*** — the blue dress (literally: the dress blue)\n\nClothing words: *la camisa* (the shirt), *el pantalón* (the trousers), *el vestido* (the dress), *los zapatos* (the shoes), *la chaqueta* (the jacket), *el sombrero* (the hat)."
    },
    {
      "id": "step-agreement-o",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Agreement: colors ending in -o",
      "body": "## Colors ending in -o agree\n\nColors that end in **-o** have **four forms** and match the gender (masculine/feminine) and number (singular/plural) of the noun.\n\n| | masculine | feminine |\n|---|---|---|\n| singular | roj**o** | roj**a** |\n| plural | roj**os** | roj**as** |\n\nSame pattern for **blanco**, **negro**, **amarillo**.\n\nExamples:\n\n- *la camisa roj**a*** — the red shirt (camisa = feminine singular)\n- *los zapatos negr**os*** — the black shoes (zapatos = masculine plural)\n- *las chaquetas blanc**as*** — the white jackets (chaquetas = feminine plural)"
    },
    {
      "id": "step-agreement-e",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Agreement: azul and verde",
      "body": "## Colors that do not end in -o\n\nColors like **azul** (blue) and **verde** (green) do not end in -o. They do **not** change for gender — masculine and feminine are the same. Only in the **plural** do they add **-es** (or -s).\n\n| | singular | plural |\n|---|---|---|\n| azul | azul | azul**es** |\n| verde | verde | verde**s** |\n\nCompare with group (a):\n\n- *el vestido **azul*** / *la chaqueta **azul*** — same form for masculine and feminine\n- BUT: *la camisa roj**a*** / *el sombrero roj**o*** — the -o color changes for gender\n\nRemember: -o colors → four forms. azul/verde → only singular/plural."
    },
